\begin_layout Section
Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Review of the Basic Equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diffusion equation describes the evolution of the composition profile
 with time as the individual components diffuse within a sample.
 These components can be either atoms or molecules, but for our purposes
 we'll assume that the diffusing species are atoms (as in a metallic sample).
 For a binary system of A and B components, we can use either 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{B}$
\end_inset

 (the respective concentrations of A and B species in atoms/volume) to describe
 the composition.
 These compositions sum to the total atomic concentration, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{0}=C_{A}+C_{B}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the molar volumes of A and B are equal to one another, then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}$
\end_inset

 is fixed, so that the following conditions hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial C_{A}}{\partial x}=-\frac{\partial C_{B}}{\partial x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial C_{A}}{\partial t}=-\frac{\partial C_{B}}{\partial t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a binary A/B alloy we can use either 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{B}$
\end_inset

 to describe the overall composition of the alloy.
 The flux of atoms is given by 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fick's first law
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fick's first law
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{i}=-D_{i}\frac{\partial C_{i}}{\partial x}\label{eq:fick's first law}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
intrinsic diffusion coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Intrinsic diffusion coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the diffusive flux of component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 referenced to a given lattice plane in the material.
 In a binary system there are two intrinsic diffusion coefficients, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}$
\end_inset

, and two diffusive fluxes, 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The time evolution of the composition is given by the continuity condition
 that relates a change in local concentration must be related to the spatial
 derivative of the flux:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial C_{i}}{\partial t}=-\frac{\partial J_{i}}{\partial x}\label{eq:flux continuity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
diffusion equation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Diffusion equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is obtained by combining Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fick's first law"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:flux continuity"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial C_{i}}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}D_{i}\left(\frac{\partial C_{i}}{\partial x}\right)\label{eq:diffusion equation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the diffusion coefficient is independent of concentration (and hence,
 independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as well) then the diffusion equation can be written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial C_{i}}{\partial t}=D_{i}\frac{\partial^{2}C_{i}}{\partial x^{2}}\label{eq:diffusion equation constant D}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diffusion equation involves a first derivative with respect to time
 an a second derivative with respect to distance, so in general we need
 an initial condition and two boundary conditions.
 Consider for example the following situation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Boundary conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=C_{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=C_{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initial condition: The concentration jumps discontinuously from 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these initial and boundary conditions, the solution to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diffusion equation constant D"

\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{a}\left(x,t\right)=\frac{C_{1}+C_{2}}{2}+\frac{C_{2}-C_{1}}{2}\mathrm{erf}\left(\frac{x}{\ell_{a}^{D}\left(t\right)}\right)\label{eq:erf diffusion solution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a}^{D}$
\end_inset

 is the following diffusion length, which enters into all diffusion problems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell_{a}^{D}\left(t\right)=2\sqrt{D_{a}t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:erf diffusion solution"

\end_inset

 is shown in Figure 
