We can also consider the situation where we have layer of material at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, which diffuses in the positive and negative directions into the bulk material.
 In this case the initial and boundary conditions are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Boundary conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pm\infty$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initial condition: All of the A component is confined to a very layer at
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, with a surface coverage (atoms/area) of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case the following solution to the diffusion equation is obtained:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{a}\left(x,t\right)=\frac{C_{s}}{\ell_{a}^{D}\left(t\right)\sqrt{\pi}}\exp\left(-\left(x/\ell_{a}^{D}\right)^{2}\right)\label{eq:thin film diffusion solution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

