\begin_layout Standard
In many cases all we need to know is the diffusion length, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a}^{D}$
\end_inset

, in order to understand what is going on at a pretty high level of detail.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a}^{D}$
\end_inset

 describes both the width of interfacial mixing for two materials that are
 brought into contact with one another (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:erf diffusion solution"

\end_inset

) and the diffusive broadening of a thin interfacial layer (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:thin film diffusion solution"

\end_inset

).
 The quantitative interpretation of the diffusion length in these two circumstan
ces is illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:diffusion length"

\end_inset

.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:diffusion length"

\end_inset

a we plot the interfacial broadening for a thin layer that is diffusing
 in the positive and negative x directions.
 The width of the diffusion profile can be characterized by the half-width
 of the peak, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, evaluated at half the total peak height.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
