\begin_layout Subsection
Mole Fractions and Volume Fractions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An assumption that we make throughout this text is that the atomic volumes
 of different chemical species are all identical, equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}.$
\end_inset

 In reality, this is almost never exactly true.
 Fortunately, it doesn't really matter when thinking about diffusion because
 we can always work with volume fractions instead of mole fractions.
 In a generalized formulation the molecular volumes of the A and B molecules
 are given by multiplying the reference volume by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, which is not necessarily the same for each molecule:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
V_{a}=N_{a}V_{0}\\
V_{b}=N_{b}V_{0}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can relate concentrations to mole fractions and volume fractions by consideri
ng a binary A/B system with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 total atoms.
 Of these, 
\begin_inset Formula $nX_{a}$
\end_inset

 are A atoms and 
\begin_inset Formula $nX_{b}$
\end_inset

 are B atoms.
 Multiplying by the the atomic volume gives the total volume of each component.
 The total volume of A atoms is 
\begin_inset Formula $nX_{a}N_{a}V_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the total volume of B atoms is 
\begin_inset Formula $nX_{b}N_{b}V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 From these expressions we obtain the following for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

, the volume fraction of A atoms in the system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\phi_{a}=\frac{nX_{a}N_{a}V_{0}}{V_{tot}}=C_{a}N_{a}V_{0}\\
\phi_{b}=\frac{nX_{a}N_{a}V_{0}}{V_{tot}}=C_{b}N_{b}V_{0}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{tot}$
\end_inset

 is the total volume of the system.
 Note that we have used 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=nX_{a}/V_{tot}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{b}=nX_{b}/V_{tot}$
\end_inset

.
 Throughout the rest of this text we generally assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}=N_{b}=1.$
\end_inset

 In the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}$
\end_inset

 and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{b}$
\end_inset

 are not equal to one we can define renormalized concentrations, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{b}^{0}$
\end_inset

 that describe the concentration of subunits of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}.$
\end_inset

 These fluxes are related to the atomic fluxes, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{b}$
\end_inset

 by multiplying by the appropriate value of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
C_{a}^{0}=C_{a}N_{a}=\phi_{a}/V_{0}\\
C_{b}^{0}=C_{b}N_{b}=\phi_{b}/V_{0}
\end{array}\label{eq:renormalized concentration}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The renormalized fluxes, 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{b}^{0}$
\end_inset

 are obtained by a similar normalization:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
J_{a}^{0}=J_{a}N_{a}\\
J_{b}^{0}=J_{b}N_{b}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fick's first law still holds for these renormalized fluxes and concentrations,
 since we are just multiplying each side of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fick's first law"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Fick's second law applies for a similar reason.
 We can also use Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:renormalized concentration"

\end_inset

 to substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\phi_{i}}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}D_{i}\left(\frac{\partial\phi_{i}}{\partial x}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bottom line of all this is that Fick's second law still applies, with
 same diffusion coefficient used for the case where the atomic volumes are
 equal, provided that we simply replace concentrations with volume fractions.
\end_layout

