\begin_layout Standard
The geometry of the Kirkendall experiment (1947) is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:kirkendall schematic"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "smigelskas_zinc_1947"

\end_inset

.
 In the experiment a small block of brass (70% copper, 30% Zn) was surrounded
 by inert, Molybdenum (Mo) wires.
 The sample was then coated with copper, and heated to a high temperature
 to allow atoms within the material to diffuse.
 In the measurement, the distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, between the Mo markers decreased as a function of time.
 This result implies that the flux of Zn out of the brass portion of the
 sample is larger than the copper flux back into the brass from the outside.
 
\end_layout

