\begin_layout Subsection
The Interdiffusion Coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, a material flux, 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

, within a material can be related to a velocity, 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 This velocity is obtained simply by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 by the reference volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

, that is used to define the diffusive flux: (
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}=1/C_{0}$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v\,\left(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\right)=J\,\left(\frac{1}{\mathrm{m^{2}\cdot s}}\right)\cdot V_{0}\,\left(\mathrm{m}^{3}\right)\label{eq:velocity vs. flux}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relevant velocity for us is a net, material velocity with respect to
 a set of inert markers, corresponding, for example to markers shown in
 the schematic representation of the Kirkendall experiment (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:kirkendall schematic"

\end_inset

).
 It is easy to see from this picture, that if there is a net material flux
 to the right (in the positive direction), the result will be a net motion
 of the markers to the left.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\ell}$
\end_inset

, the net velocity of the markers with respect to the ends of the samples,
 is determined by using -
\begin_inset Formula $\left(J_{a}+J_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 as the relevant flux in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:velocity vs. flux"

\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{\ell}=-\left(J_{a}+J_{b}\right)V_{0}\label{eq:lattice velocity vs. flux}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will often find it useful to use mole fractions instead of concentrations
 in our expressions, so we need to keep the following relationship in mind:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{i}=X_{i}C_{0}\label{eq:conc. vs. volume fraction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

=A we can differentiate Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:conc. vs. volume fraction"

\end_inset

 to obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial X_{a}}{\partial x}=\frac{1}{C_{0}}\frac{\partial C_{a}}{\partial x}\label{eq:X and C derivatives}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now combine Fick's first law (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fick's first law"

\end_inset

) with Eqs.
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lattice velocity vs. flux"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:conc. vs. volume fraction"

\end_inset

 to obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{\ell}=\left(D_{a}-D_{b}\right)\frac{\partial X_{a}}{\partial x}\label{eq:lattice velocity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the velocity that individual planes are moving with respect to a
 fixed position in the sample that is far from the interface (the ends of
 the sample, for example).
 The fluxes obtained from Fick's first law are defined in terms of a reference
 plane that is moving with a velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 We can also define fluxes of A and B atoms across stationary planes, and
 we refer to these fluxes as 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{b}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 We can get 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 by adding 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\ell}C_{a}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\ell}C_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the net flux of A atoms across a fixed plane in space due to the lattice
 plane velocity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{a}^{'}=-D_{a}\frac{\partial C_{a}}{\partial x}+v_{\ell}C_{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can combine this expression with Eq.
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 to get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{a}^{'}=-D_{a}\frac{\partial C_{a}}{\partial x}+\left(D_{a}-D_{b}\right)C_{a}\frac{\partial X_{a}}{\partial x}\label{eq:Ja prime intermediate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}/C_{0}=X_{a}$
\end_inset

, we can combine Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X and C derivatives"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ja prime intermediate"

\end_inset

 to obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{a}^{'}=-D_{a}\frac{\partial C_{a}}{\partial x}+\left(D_{a}-D_{b}\right)X_{a}\frac{\partial C_{a}}{\partial x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After a bit of algebra, keeping in mind that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a}+X_{b}=1$
\end_inset

, we obtain the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
