\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{a}^{'}=-\left[D_{a}X_{b}+X_{a}D_{b}\right]\frac{\partial C_{a}}{\partial x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can define an 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
interdiffusion coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Interdiffusion coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{D}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{D} & =\left[X_{b}D_{a}+X_{a}D_{b}\right]\label{eq:interdiffusion coefficient}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with this definition we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{a}^{\prime}=-\tilde{D}\frac{\partial C_{a}}{\partial x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar approach can be used to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{b}^{\prime}=-J_{b}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and that the same value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{D}$
\end_inset

 can be used to relate 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{b}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial C_{b}}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, this same value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{D}$
\end_inset

 now appears in Fick's second law, where we can see from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:interdiffusion coefficient"

\end_inset

 that the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{D}$
\end_inset

 is generally going to be composition dependent.
 The concentration profile therefore evolves according to the time-dependent
 solution of the following form of Fick's second law:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
