\begin_layout Subsection
Connection to thermodynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At equilibrium the chemical potential of component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 is not constant, then we must have diffusive fluxes as the system move
 towards equilibrium.
 It's not a gradient in concentration that generates the flux, it's really
 the gradient in the chemical potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
show schematic of coexisting phases
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A simple example illustrating this point is the abrupt change in concentration
 that exists at an equilibrated interface between two coexisting phases,
 shown as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phases in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:alpha beta interface"

\end_inset

.
 Even though there is a large composition gradient at the interface, there
 is no diffusion for an equilibrated system because the chemical potential
 is spatially uniform.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/alpha beta interface.svg
	width 40text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic representation of the interface between 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phases.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:alpha beta interface"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This example illustrates the fact that diffusion involves more than just
 concentration gradients, but involves thermodynamic factors as well.
 In order to account for these we need to revisit Fick's first law, but
 write things in terms of the chemical potentials.
 The flux of B atoms is can be written as the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{b}$
\end_inset

 and a diffusive velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{b}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the average velocity at which the B atoms are moving.
 This velocity is related to the concentration gradient by a mobility coefficien
t, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{b}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{b}=-M_{b}\frac{\partial\mu_{b}}{\partial x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{b}$
\end_inset

 must be positive.
 Atoms always move down a chemical potential potential gradient, although
 in some cases diffusion may take place up a concentration gradient (more
 on this in 316-2).
 We can use the previous expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{b}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the following expression for the diffusive flux of B atoms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{b}=C_{b}v_{b}=-M_{b}C_{b}\frac{\partial\mu_{b}}{\partial X_{b}}\frac{\partial X_{b}}{\partial x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X and C derivatives"

\end_inset

 to write this in terms of a concentration gradient:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{b}=-M_{b}X_{b}\frac{\partial\mu_{b}}{\partial X_{b}}\frac{\partial C_{b}}{\partial x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing to Fick's first law (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fick's first law"

\end_inset

), we obtain the following for 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{b}=M_{b}X_{b}\frac{\partial\mu_{b}}{\partial X_{b}}\label{eq:Db vs mobility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tracer diffusion coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}$
\end_inset

 in the dilute limit, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{b}$
\end_inset

 is dominated by the configurational entropy of mixing.
 In this limit the concentration dependence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{b}$
\end_inset

 is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{b}=\mu_{b}^{0}+k_{B}T\ln X_{b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the tracer diffusion coefficient for the B atoms is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{b}^{*}=k_{B}TM_{b}\label{eq:dbstar vs mobility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by comparing Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Db vs mobility"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dbstar vs mobility"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{b}=\frac{D_{b}^{*}X_{b}}{k_{B}T}\frac{\partial\mu_{b}}{\partial X_{b}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Composition dependent tracer diffusion coefficients can also be defined,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}^{*}$
\end_inset

 does not always correspond to the diffusion coefficient of B atoms in an
 alloy that is almost entirely made up of B.
 We can also imagine an alloy of any composition, but where we label a small
 fraction of B atoms (by isotopic substitution, for example).
 In this case the diffusing species is itself dilute, but the the alloy
 in which it is diffusing can have any composition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary of Diffusion in a Binary System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have defined three interrelated types diffusion coefficients: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{D}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Here we provide a brief summary of these different diffusion coefficients
 and the relationships between them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{D}$
\end_inset

: The interdiffusion coefficient (often referred to as the mutual diffusion
 coefficient).
 If you are interested in the time-dependent evolution of the composition
 profile, this is the diffusion coefficient that you use when you are solving
 the diffusion equation:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial C_{b}}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\tilde{D}\left(C_{b}\right)\left(\frac{\partial C_{b}}{\partial x}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
note that for a binary system, we only need to specify one of the compositions,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=C_{0}-C_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that in general, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{D}$
\end_inset

 depends on the composition, so cannot be treated as a constant.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $D_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}$
\end_inset

: The intrinsic diffusion coefficients for the individual components.
 These are important for two reasons.
 First, they are needed if you want to describe motions of atomic planes
 relative to the external boundaries of the sample (the Kirkendall effect).
 This motion was determined from the the atomic fluxes relative to atomic
 planes, as opposed to fixed points in space.
 These fluxes are determined by the appropriate intrinsic diffusion coefficient.
 For example, for the B component, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{b}=-D_{b}\frac{\partial C_{b}}{\partial x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, predictive models of interdiffusion are generally based on the relationshi
p between these intrinsic diffusion coefficients and the interdiffusion
 coefficient through the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{D} & =\left[X_{b}D_{a}+X_{a}D_{b}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $D_{a}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}^{*}$
\end_inset

: The tracer diffusion coefficients for the individual components.
 Imagine a single atom in a homogeneous material.
 The tracer diffusion coefficient describes the probability that the atom
 has diffused a certain distance in a given period of time.
 These diffusion coefficients are purely kinetic parameters.
 Unlike the interdiffusion and intrinsic diffusion coefficients, they are
 not affected by the thermodynamics of the system.
 In general, values of the tracer diffusion coefficients will depend on
 the concentration of the material in which the tracer atoms are diffusing.
 The special cases of 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{a}^{*}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{b}^{*}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}=1$
\end_inset

 are self diffusion coefficients.
 The intrinsic diffusion coefficients are related to the tracer diffusion
 coefficients through the following relationship:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{b}=\frac{D_{b}^{*}X_{b}}{k_{B}T}\frac{\partial\mu_{b}}{\partial X_{b}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Diffusion in Ternary Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Atomic diffusion in ternary systems is driven by chemical potential gradients,
 just as it is does in binary systems.
 In systems with more than two components, however, the composition is no
 longer specified by a single composition variable.
 Some interesting effects can be observed in this case, as exemplified by
 carbon diffusion in Fe-Si-C ternary alloys .
 The carbon chemical potential is now a function of the concentration of
 both the silicon and carbon in the alloy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{c}=f\left(X_{Si},X_{C}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diffusion coefficient of carbon is much larger than the diffusion coefficien
t for silicon (
\begin_inset Formula $D_{c}\gg D_{Si}$
\end_inset

), so we can assume that the silicon remains stationary during a diffusion
 experiment, as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ternary diffusion"

\end_inset

.
 Silicon and carbon have a unfavorable thermodynamic interaction within
 the alloy, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{c}$
\end_inset

 increases with increasing silicon content, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{Si}$
\end_inset

.
 In order for the carbon chemical potential to remain constant across and
 interface between two regions of differing Si content, the carbon concentration
 in the region with low Si content needs to be smaller than the carbon concentra
tion in the region with high Si content.
 This chemical potential discontinuity at the interface is eliminated by
 the jump of carbon atoms from the left (high Si side) to the right (low
 Si side) of the interface.
 Diffusion then continues from left to right, down the carbon potential
 gradient that has been established.
\end_layout

