\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Exercise:
\series default
 From the critical resolved shear stress for single crystal aluminum shown
 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Critical-resolved-shear stress"

\end_inset

, calculate the minimum force (in pounds) that must be applied to a one
 half inch diameter rod of single crystal Al to deform plastically.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 The critical resolved shear stress for pure, single crystal Al is 148 psi,
 so we need to figure out what tensile stress on the sample will produce
 this value for the resolved shear stress, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{rss}$
\end_inset

.
 The smallest value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{rss}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the critical value of 148 occurs for the slip system with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\lambda=45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

, so from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:resolved shear stress"

\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=2\tau_{rss}=296$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying by the cross sectional area of the rod gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\,\mathrm{=\left(296\,psi\right)\cdot\pi\cdot\left(0.25\,in\right)^{2}=58\,pounds}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is a pretty small force, and is much less than the force required to
 deform a stock piece of aluminum that I would find in the machine shop.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why is the force to deform a single crystal so low? We'll start by considering
 what we would expect for the critical resolved shear stress if the shear
 deformation were to occur by the sliding of atomic planes over one another,
 as shown conceptually in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:slip of close packed planes"

\end_inset

.
 We refer to the stress required to slide these planes over one another
 as the dislocation-free critical resolved shear stress, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{crss}^{0}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

