\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}\times\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 cross product
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dislocations ! 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}\times\vec{s}$
\end_inset

 cross product
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concept of the Burgers circuit is a useful formalism that can always
 be used to specify the Burgers vector for a given dislocation.
 The confusing part about the procedure is that the sign of the Burgers
 vector depends on some arbitrary conventions that are not used the same
 way by everyone.
 For example, our convention is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 as the vector linking the start to the finish of the Burgers circuit in
 the perfect crystal (linking points s to f in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Burgers circuit screw"

\end_inset

), but you can find plenty of other people who draw the vector the other
 way around (drawing 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 from point f to point s).
 Nevertheless, we remove any ambiguity by always using this 'start-to-finish'
 definition for the Burgers vector.
 Similarly, we remove ambiguity regarding the direction in which we take
 the Burgers circuit by always doing it the same way.
 In our case we use the right hand rule, directing our thumb along 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 and drawing the circuit in the direction in which our fingers are pointing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, the ambiguity introduced by our definition of the direction
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 along the dislocation line is impossible to remove.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Burgers circuit screw"

\end_inset

 we defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 so that it points along the negative z direction, but there's no reason
 that we couldn't have defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}$
\end_inset

 so that it is directed in the positive z direction instead.
 We end up with a Burgers vector that points in one of two opposite directions,
 depending on how we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 in the first place.
 The good news is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}_{d}$
\end_inset

, the vector cross product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 is independent of our convention for defining the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}$
\end_inset

.
 As a reminder, the vector cross product between vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows, as illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Definition of nd"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "_cross_2014"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{n}_{d}=\vec{b}\times\hat{s}=\vec{\left|b\right|}\left|\hat{s}\right|\sin\theta\hat{n}=b\sin\theta\hat{n}_{d}\label{eq:nd definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{d}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector in the direction perpendicular to the plane containing
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

.
 It's orientation is defined using the right hand rule: We place our right
 hand along 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

, with our fingers oriented in the positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 direction.
 Our right thumb is then pointed along 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

