\begin_layout Subsection
Dislocation Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dislocation disrupts the regularity of the lattice, and introduces strain
 into the sample.
 The strain field that results from the presence of a dislocation has a
 very long range, and can easily be more than 100 times the unit cell dimension.
 As a result the total strain energy is very large as well.
 This strain field and the energy associated with it is important because
 it provides a mechanism for dislocations to interact with one another over
 long distances.
 In essence, dislocations 'talk' to each other through these strain fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Screw Dislocations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a screw dislocation we can use some simple concepts to calculate this
 strain energy, so we'll start with this example.
 Our starting point is that the material surrounding a screw dislocation
 is in a state of pure shear, with shear deformation as defined in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:shear strain"

\end_inset

.
 We see this by considering a cylindrical portion of the material around
 a screw dislocation, using the illustration in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:screw dislocation strain field"

\end_inset

.
 The displacement applied across the dislocation is given by the Burgers
 vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:screw dislocation strain field"

\end_inset

a).
 (When referring to the magnitude of the Burgers vector we'll drop the vector
 symbol and just use the 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

).
 If we unwrap the circumference of the cylinder at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 from the dislocation line (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:screw dislocation strain field"

\end_inset

b) we see that the shear displacement of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is applied over a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi r$
\end_inset

.
 The cylinder has been unwrapped in the circumferential direction, 
\emph on
i.e.
 
\emph default
the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 direction, and the displacement is along the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 direction so we have the following for th shear strain, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{z\theta}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/screw dislocation strains.svg
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Strain field around a screw dislocation that is centered along the z axis.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:screw dislocation strain field"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distortion is pure shear, with a shear strain at a radius of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 given by the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e_{z\theta}=\frac{b}{2\pi r}\label{eq:screw disloc shear stratin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that as 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow0,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{z\theta}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The strain can't really go to infinity, so we have a problem here that
 we're going to have to deal with eventually.
 The elastic stress is obtained by multiplying by the shear modulus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{z\theta}=\frac{Gb}{2\pi r}\label{eq:shear discloc shear stress}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The elastic strain energy per unit volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{v}$
\end_inset

 is obtained from the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{v}=\int_{0}^{e_{r\theta}}\tau_{z\theta}de_{z\theta}=\frac{G}{2}e_{z\theta}^{2}\label{eq:energy from stress strain integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dimensionally this makes sense, since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has units of force/area, or energy/volume.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can combine Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:screw disloc shear stratin"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:energy from stress strain integral"

\end_inset

 to obtain the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{v}=\frac{G}{2}\left(\frac{b}{2\pi r}\right)^{2}\label{eq:screw dislocation Ev}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the total dislocation energy for the screw dislocation, which we
 refer to as, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}$
\end_inset

, we need to integrate for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 (from 0 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

), all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (from 0 to 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the length of the dislocation), and all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (from 0 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{s}=\int_{0}^{2\pi}\int_{0}^{h}\int_{0}^{^{r_{max}}}E_{v}\left(\theta,z,r\right)d\theta dzdr
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our case the system is radially symmetric, with an energy density that
 depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 but not on 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 So we get a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 from the integration over 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 from the integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{s}=2\pi h\int_{0}^{r_{max}}E_{v}\left(r\right)dr
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{v}$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:screw dislocation Ev"

\end_inset

 into this equation gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{s}=\frac{Gb^{2}h}{4\pi}{\displaystyle {\displaystyle \int_{0}^{r_{max}}}\frac{1}{r}dr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After integration we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{s}=\frac{Gb^{2}h}{4\pi}{\displaystyle \left[\ln r_{max}-\ln0\right]}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have a problem here because 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln0=-\infty$
\end_inset

.
 This is because for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, the shear strain goes to infinity and we can no longer use the simple,
 continuum picture of linear elasticity to describe what is going on.
 Instead what we typically do is separate out a core energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}^{core}$
\end_inset

 that corresponds to the strain energy inside some small core radius, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We do this simply be adding 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}^{core}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}$
\end_inset

 and replacing the lower bound on the integration from 0 to 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{o}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{s}=E_{s}^{core}+\frac{Gb^{2}h}{4\pi}{\displaystyle \ln\left(\frac{r_{max}}{r_{0}}\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can generally choose 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 so that it is large enough so that our assumption of linear elasticity
 holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $r>r_{0}$
\end_inset

, yet it is small enough so that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}^{core}$
\end_inset

 is a relatively small fraction of the overall dislocation energy.
 In this case we can ignore the core energy and approximate the dislocation
 energy as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{s}\approx\frac{Gb^{2}h}{4\pi}{\displaystyle \ln\left(\frac{r_{max}}{r_{0}}\right)}\label{eq:screw dislocation energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Edge Dislocations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stress field for an this case is much more complicated, as illustrated
 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:edge dislocation stress fields"

\end_inset

.
 The distinctive features of the strain field are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the slip plane itself the material is in a state of pure shear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Above the slip plane there is compressive component to the strain field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Below the slip plane there is a tensile component to the strain field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more detailed calculation shows that the strain still decays as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r$
\end_inset

, with an expression for the edge dislocation energy per length that is
 similar to the expression obtained for a screw dislocation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{s}\approx\frac{Gb^{2}h}{4\pi\left(1-\nu\right)}\ln\left(\frac{r_{max}}{r_{0}}\right)\label{eq:edge dislocatioon energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is Poisson's ratio.
 Typically 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx0.3$
\end_inset

 for most metals.
\end_layout

