\begin_layout Subsubsection
General Comments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following general comments are valid for edge, screw and mixed dislocations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Elastic strain energy scales with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln r$
\end_inset

 so it has a very long range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The boundary conditions matter, so the energy depends on the shape of the
 sample.
 A small crystal with low value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max}$
\end_inset

 will have a lower dislocation energy than a large crystal with a very large
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Energy scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Dislocations with small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are therefore preferred, which is why the Burgers vector in a material
 corresponds to the smallest interatomic spacing in the material.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Energy scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Energy is proportional to the length of the dislocation.
 This means the strain energy will decreases as the line length decreases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This last point seems trivial at first, but it has some important consequences.
 Consider for example a dislocation loop.
 If the radius of a circular loop decreases, the energy associated with
 the loop will decrease as well.
 There's a line tension acting on the loop causing it to contract.
 This tension is like the tension in a rubber band that once to squeeze
 things inward, and can be viewed as a driving force for the dislocation
 loop to shrink in size.
 An applied stress can cause a dislocation loop to grow instead of shrink,
 and this will be considered later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's compare some numbers to see how the dislocation energy compares to
 the energy of other defects, like vacancies, for example.
 To do this we'll estimate the energy per atomic length along a screw dislocatio
n line by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $h=b$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:screw dislocation energy"

\end_inset

.
 We'll also assume typical values for the other parameters in the expression
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

=0.3 nm, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}=1$
\end_inset

nm.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max}=1\,\mu m$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $G=3x10^{10}$
\end_inset

 Pa:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{s}\approx\frac{Gb^{3}}{4\pi}{\displaystyle \ln\left(\frac{r_{max}}{r_{0}}\right)=\mathrm{\frac{\left(3x10^{10}\,Pa\right)\left(3x10^{-10}\,m\right)^{3}}{4\pi}\ln\left(\frac{1000\,nm}{1\,nm}\right)=4.5x10^{-19}\,J}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more convenient energy scale on an atomic basis is the electron volt,
 which we obtain from the energy in Joules by dividing by the electron charge
 (1.6x10
\begin_inset Formula $^{-19}$
\end_inset

 C).
 In these units the energy per atom along the dislocation line is 2.8 eV.
 This energy of comparable magnitude to typical vacancy formation energies
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 1eV, but is actually larger because of the nature of the long-range strain
 field that is produced around a dislocation.
\end_layout

