\begin_layout Subsection
Effect of Applied Stress
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The line tension acts to decrease the area of a dislocation loop, but we
 need loops to expand in order for a material to plastically deform.
 So how does an applied stress induce a force on a dislocation? An applied
 shear stress, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 results in an additional force per unit length, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s}^{\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 It's easiest to visualize the relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s}^{\tau}$
\end_inset

 for an edge dislocation, as we illustrate in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fs for screw dislocation"

\end_inset

.
 To do this we use an energy balance.
 When the dislocation has propagated across the entire sample a total applied
 shear force, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, results in a net translation of the material above the slip plane by an
 amount given by the Burgers vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The total work put into the system is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $Pb$
\end_inset

 (force times displacement).
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=P/w\ell$
\end_inset

 this total work is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
work=w\ell\tau b\label{eq:external work on dislocation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work goes into moving the dislocation, and must be equal to the force
 applied to the dislocation multiplied by the distance the dislocation moves
 as it translates across the sample.
 In our notation this distance is the sample width, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, so we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
work=F_{s}^{\tau}\ell w\label{eq:work to move dislocation in terms of Fs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equating these two expressions for the work gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{s}^{\tau}=\tau b\label{eq:dislocation force}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the force per unit length acting on the dislocation is simply the shear
 stress multiplied by the magnitude of the Burgers vector.
\end_layout

