\begin_layout Standard
Now we can look at the stress required to expand a circular dislocation
 loop.
 We'll assume that the energy/length of the dislocation is a constant.
 In other words, we are neglecting the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\nu$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:edge dislocatioon energy"

\end_inset

 that gives a small energy difference between edge and screw dislocations.
 The total force per unit length acting on a circular dislocation loop is
 the sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s}^{r}$
\end_inset

, which acts toward the center of the loop and therefore negative, and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s}^{\tau}$
\end_inset

, which for an appropriately aligned shear stress is positive:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
