\begin_layout Plain Layout
Story about the Wright brothers airplane.
 Started out with cast Aluminum.
 Al didn't pour right when poured into the mold.
 So they added a small amount of copper.
 It was put into a sand mold, and the solid slowly cooled.
 Very small amounts of Cu precipitates were formed, which strengthened the
 alloy.
 The Wright brothers got it right be accident, but all aerospace alloys
 still contain Cu (and a bunch of other alloying elements) that form precipitate
s.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So why do precipitates strengthen a material? The answer is connected to
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:tau star from line tension"

\end_inset

.
 Consider a dislocation that is moving toward two precipitates.
 The applied stress results in a force per unit length, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s}^{\tau}$
\end_inset

 that moves the dislocation.
 The pinning of the dislocation between the precipitates results in a curvature,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, with an associated stress 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{*}$
\end_inset

 that must be applied in order for the dislocation to move.
 The maximum value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{*}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the minimum value of the dislocation curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, which is equal to half the interparticle spacing.
 For optimum strengthening, what we want very small precipitates with a
 correspondingly small interparticle spacing.
\end_layout

