\begin_layout Standard
Dislocations interact through the long range strain fields induced by the
 dislocations.
 Consider two screw dislocations with Burgers vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 that separated by 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 The stress at dislocation 2 due to the presence of dislocation 1 is given
 by Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shear discloc shear stress"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{\tau}=\frac{G\vec{b}}{2\pi d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use a vector notation for the stress here to remind us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 the force associated with the shear stress is directed along 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This stress induces a force on the dislocation, given by Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dislocation force"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{s}^{\tau}=\frac{G\vec{b}_{2}\cdot\vec{b}_{1}}{2\pi d}\label{eq:Fs for interacting screw dislocations}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are pointing in the same direction, the force is positive and the interaction
 is repulsive.
 If they are pointing in the opposite direction, the force is negative (attracti
ve).
 Because the force scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/d$
\end_inset

 it has a very long range.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also make a qualitative argument based on the energetics to see what
 is going on.
 From Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Fs for interacting screw dislocations"

\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\propto b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If the dislocations have opposite signs, the dislocation come together
 and the net 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is zero.
 If they have the same sign, then they form a total Burgers vector with
 a magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $2b$
\end_inset

, and an energy of 
\begin_inset Formula $4b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So the energy is twice as large as it was originally.
 The energy as a function of separation must look the plot shown in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:screw dislocation interactions"

\end_inset

.
 If the energy of each individual dislocation is 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $d\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, then the total dislocation energy at 
\begin_inset Formula $d=0$
\end_inset

 is zero for dislocations of opposite sign and 
\begin_inset Formula $4E_{1}$
\end_inset

 for dislocations of the same sign.
\end_layout

