\begin_layout Plain Layout
The first and second laws of thermodynamics state that at equilibrium the
 energy (
\begin_inset Formula $E)$
\end_inset

 of the system is a minimum under conditions of constant entropy (
\begin_inset Formula $S)$
\end_inset

, volume (
\begin_inset Formula $V)$
\end_inset

 and number of atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{i})$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\delta E\right|_{S,V,n_{i}}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E=0$
\end_inset

.
 include constraints with lagrange multipliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
T, P, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 = constant This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
