 = constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

= constant,
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How can we develop a generalized description of interfacial thermodynamics
 that is valid for all types of interface (crystalline, amorphous, narrow,
 broad, etc.)? Fortunately, this was done by Gibbs even before atoms were
 discovered (c.
 1880)! Our basic assumption is that all quantities vary across the interface
 in a continuous manner, like the density plot shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Interfacial-profile."

\end_inset

.
 We need to develop the corresponding condition for the inhomogeneous interfacia
l region of finite width.
 We begin by considering the interface between two phases, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 As shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:general alpha beta interface"

\end_inset

 we can separate the system in to three regions: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 bulk phase regions where the properties are completely uniform, and an
 interfacial region 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, where the properties (
\begin_inset Formula $S,\,n_{i},$
\end_inset

 etc.
 are non-uniform).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/general alpha beta interface.svg
	width 45text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Formal representation of the interfacial region between 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phases.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:general alpha beta interface"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by recognizing that the total energy is the sum of the energies
 of the three different regions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=E^{\alpha}+E^{\beta}+E^{I}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This same summation holds for the total entropy and for the number of atoms
 of each component in the system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=S^{\alpha}+S^{\beta}+S^{I}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n_{i}=n_{i}^{\alpha}+n_{i}^{\beta}+n_{i}^{I}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we haven't invoked any thermodynamic principles.
 We just divided the entropy, energy into portions that reside in each of
 the three zones of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:general alpha beta interface"

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

).
 Now we invoke the second law of thermodynamics which for us we word in
 the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At equilibrium we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E=0$
\end_inset

 (energy is minimized) at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta E=\delta E^{\alpha}+\delta E^{\beta}+\delta E^{I}=0\label{eq:delta E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each of the terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in a sum involving partial derivatives with respect to
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 For example, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 we have: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta E^{\alpha}=\frac{\partial E^{\alpha}}{\partial S^{\alpha}}\delta S^{\alpha}+\frac{\partial E^{\alpha}}{\partial V^{\alpha}}\delta V^{\alpha}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\frac{\partial E^{\alpha}}{\partial n_{i}}\delta n_{i}\label{eq:delta E alpha}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also use the following expressions for the chemical potentials and
 the temperature:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T^{\alpha}\equiv\frac{\partial E^{\alpha}}{\partial S^{\alpha}}\label{eq:temp as partial deriv. of free energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{i}^{\alpha}\equiv\frac{\partial E^{\alpha}}{\partial n_{i}^{\alpha}}\label{eq:chemical pot. as parital deriv. of free energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{\alpha}\equiv-\frac{\partial E^{\alpha}}{\partial V}\label{eq:pressure as partial deriv of energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We'll fix the boundaries between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 region in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:general alpha beta interface"

\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta V^{\alpha}=\delta V^{\beta}=\delta V^{I}=0$
\end_inset

 and the volume terms in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta E alpha"

\end_inset

 disappear.
 With this assumption, and the definitions of the temperature (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:temp as partial deriv. of free energy"

\end_inset

) and chemical potential (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chemical pot. as parital deriv. of free energy"

\end_inset

), we can rewrite Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta E alpha"

\end_inset

 as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta E^{\alpha}=T^{\alpha}\delta S^{\alpha}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{\alpha}\delta n_{i}\label{eq:del E alpha - fixed volume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exactly analogous expressions can be written down for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{I}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta E^{\beta}=T^{\beta}\delta S^{\beta}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{\beta}\delta n_{i}\label{eq:del E beta - fixed volume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta E^{I}=T^{I}\delta S^{I}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{I}\delta n_{i}\label{eq:del E I fixed volume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now substitute these expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{I}$
\end_inset

 into Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta E"

\end_inset

 to obtain the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T^{\alpha}\delta S^{\alpha}+T^{\beta}\delta S^{\beta}+T^{I}\delta S^{I}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{\alpha}\delta n_{i}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{\beta}\delta n_{i}^{\beta}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{I}\delta n_{i}^{\beta}=0\label{eq:delta E-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can consider the constraints on the system: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta n_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 (a closed thermodynamic system at equilibrium).
 In our case these constraints can be written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta S=\delta S^{\alpha}+\delta S^{\beta}+\delta S^{I}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta n_{i}=\delta n_{i}^{\alpha}+\delta n_{i}^{\beta}+\delta n_{i}^{I}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use these two equations to eliminate 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta n_{i}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta E-1"

\end_inset

 by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $-\delta S^{I}-\delta S^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\delta n_{i}^{I}-\delta n_{i}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta n_{i}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T^{\alpha}\left(-\delta S^{I}-\delta S^{\beta}\right)+T^{\beta}\delta S^{\beta}+T^{I}\delta S^{I}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{\alpha}\left(-\delta n_{i}^{I}-\delta n_{i}^{\beta}\right)+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{\beta}\delta n_{i}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\mu_{i}^{I}\delta n_{i}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression can be rearranged to the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta S^{\beta}\left(T^{\beta}-T^{\alpha}\right)+\delta S^{I}\left(T^{I}-T^{\alpha}\right)+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\left(\mu_{i}^{\beta}-\mu_{i}^{\alpha}\right)\delta n_{i}^{\beta}+{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\left(\mu_{i}^{I}-\mu_{i}^{\alpha}\right)\delta n_{i}^{I}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the terms in brackets must be zero, since this must hold true for any
 variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{I}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{\beta}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}^{I}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{\alpha}=T^{\beta}=T^{I}$
\end_inset

 (uniform temperature) and that the chemical potentials are uniform everywhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Dividing Surface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At a planar interface, we still get the usual thermodynamic condition that
 the temperature and chemical potentials are uniform everywhere at equilibrium.
 But what about pressure effects? What if 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta V^{\alpha}\ne0$
\end_inset

? To answer these questions we will make a relatively large conceptual leap
 and replace the real system where the interfacial has some finite width
 with an equivalent model system where the the interface is a true surface
 with no volume.
 This model system is obtained by extending bulk phase properties all the
 way up to the fictitious location of the dividing surface, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, where we have the two phases 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 in our example directly in contact with one another.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/dividing surface.svg
	width 70text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Conceptual representation of the replacement of a continuous concentration
 gradient a single dividing surface, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, that has no width.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:dividing surface"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once we specify the precise location of the dividing surface we can determine
 the number of atoms that are associated with the th interface.
 Once we know where the dividing surface is, we also know the volumes of
 each phase, 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\beta}.$
\end_inset

 Multiplying by the bulk phase concentration gives the total number of atoms
 in each phase:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
n_{i}^{\alpha}=C_{i}^{\alpha}V^{\alpha}\\
n_{i}^{\beta}=C_{i}^{\beta}V^{\beta}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In general, the total number of atoms of component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

, is not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}^{\alpha}+n_{i}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 The excess is associated with the interfaces, and is referred to as 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}^{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n_{i}^{\Sigma}=n_{i}-n_{i}^{\alpha}-n_{i}^{\beta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We commonly divide by the interfacial area, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, to get an interfacial excess of component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 per area, which we define as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{i}\equiv n_{i}^{\Sigma}/A
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also define an interfacial energy (
\begin_inset Formula $E^{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

) and an interfacial entropy (
\begin_inset Formula $S^{\Sigma})$
\end_inset

 in a similar way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E^{\Sigma}=E-E^{\alpha}-E^{\beta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S^{\Sigma}=S-S^{\alpha}-S^{\beta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that is is generally fairly obvious where we should put the dividing
 surface (at least approximately), although the detailed location we choose
 will affect the exact values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now proceed in a fashion that is similar to what we did in the previous
 section.
 The expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 are the same as Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:del E alpha - fixed volume"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:del E beta - fixed volume"

\end_inset

, but we will no longer insist that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta V^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta V^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 are zero:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta E^{\alpha}=T^{\alpha}\delta S^{\alpha}-P^{\alpha}dV^{\alpha}+\sum\mu_{i}^{\alpha}\delta n_{i}^{\alpha}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta E^{\beta}=T^{\beta}\delta S^{\beta}-P^{\beta}dV^{\beta}+\sum\mu_{i}^{\beta}\delta n_{i}^{\beta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interface is different from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phases in that it has no volume, but it has an area, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E^{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

, the differential of the energy associated with the interface, we replace
 the partial derivative term involving 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta V$
\end_inset

 with one involving 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A$
\end_inset

.
 The version of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta E alpha"

\end_inset

 that holds for the interface can therefore be written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta E^{\Sigma}=\frac{\partial E^{\Sigma}}{\partial S^{\Sigma}}\delta S^{\Sigma}+\sum\frac{\partial E^{\Sigma}}{\partial n_{i}^{\Sigma}}\delta n_{i}^{\Sigma}+\frac{\partial E^{\Sigma}}{\partial A^{\Sigma}}\delta A^{\Sigma}\label{eq:delta E for interface}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The partial derivative of the energy with respect to area that appears in
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta E for interface"

\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
interfacial energy
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Interfacial energy
\end_layout

\end_inset

 between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{\alpha\beta}=\frac{\partial E^{\Sigma}}{\partial A^{\Sigma}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this definition, and the expressions given previously for the temperature
 (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:temp as partial deriv. of free energy"

\end_inset

) and chemical potential (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chemical pot. as parital deriv. of free energy"

\end_inset

) we obtain the following for the differential in the energy associated
 with the interface:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
