name "fig:melting of a curved interface"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equilibrium condition between the solid and liquid is obtained by equating
 the chemical potentials in the solid and liquid phase.
 For a single component system, the chemical potential on a molar basis
 (energy per mole of atoms as opposed to energy per atom) is equivalent
 to the molar free energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 What we need to do is find the temperature where the molar free energy
 of the material in the solid phase, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{m}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the molar free energy in the liquid phase (
\begin_inset Formula $G_{m}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{m}^{s}(T,P^{s})=G_{m}^{\ell}(T,P^{\ell})\label{eq:gms=gml for critical nucleus}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that we are interested in the case where the temperature is not necessarily
 equal to the equilibrium melting temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T\neq T_{m})$
\end_inset

.
 This temperature difference arises from the fact that the pressure in the
 solid and liquid phases differs by an amount given by the Laplace pressure
 difference, 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{s}-P^{\ell}=2\gamma/R$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that the differences between 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

 and between 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 are small, so we can get away with retaining only the first derivative
 terms in Taylor series expansions for 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{m}^{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{m}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
G_{m}^{s}(T,\,P^{s})=G_{m}^{s}(T_{m},\,P^{\ell})+\left.\frac{\partial G_{m}^{s}}{\partial T}\right|_{P^{\ell},T_{m}}(T-T_{m})+\left.\frac{\partial G_{m}^{s}}{\partial P}\right|_{P^{\ell},T_{m}}(P^{S}-P^{\ell})\\
G_{m}^{\ell}(T,P^{\ell})=G_{m}^{\ell}(T_{m},\,P^{\ell})+\left.\frac{\partial G_{m}^{\ell}}{\partial T}\right|_{P^{L},\,T_{m}}(T-T_{m})
\end{cases}\label{eq:gm taylor expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can use the following thermodynamic definitions: 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$S_{m}^{S}$"
description "Molar entropy of the critical nucleus"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$S_{m}^{L}$"
description "Molar entropy of the liquid phase"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$V_{m}^{S}$"
description "Molar volume of the solid phase"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial G_{m}^{s}}{\partial T}=–S_{m}^{s},\,\frac{\partial G_{m}^{\ell}}{\partial T}=–S_{m}^{\ell},\,\frac{\partial G_{m}^{s}}{\partial P}=V_{m}^{s}\label{eq:maxwell def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Combination of Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gm taylor expansion"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:maxwell def"

\end_inset

 gives the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
G_{m}^{s}(T,P^{s})=G_{m}^{s}+(T_{m},P^{\ell})\text{–}S_{m}^{s}(T-T_{m})+V_{m}^{s}(P^{s}-P^{\ell})\\
G_{m}^{\ell}(T,P^{\ell})=G_{m}^{\ell}(T_{m},P^{\ell})\text{–}S_{m}^{\ell}(T-T_{m})
\end{cases}\label{eq:taylor gm2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a planar interface (
\begin_inset Formula $R=\infty$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{\ell}=P^{s}$
\end_inset

, and the liquid and solids are at equilibrium at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=T_{m}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{m}^{\ell}(T_{m},P^{\ell})=G_{m}^{s}(T_{m,}P^{\ell})\label{eq:gm bulk eq'm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the differences, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{m},\,\Delta S_{m},\,\Delta T$
\end_inset

 in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\mbox{\ensuremath{H_{m}\equiv H_{m}^{\ell}-}\ensuremath{H_{m}^{S},}}\,\Delta S_{m}\equiv S_{m}^{\ell}-S_{m}^{s},\,\Delta T\equiv T_{m}-T\label{eq:delta defs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we combine Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gms=gml for critical nucleus"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:taylor gm2"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gm bulk eq'm"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta defs"

\end_inset

 to obtain the following for the temperature difference:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{m}-T=\frac{\left(P^{s}-P^{l}\right)V_{m}^{s}}{\Delta S_{m}}\label{eq:delta T entropy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The enthalpy of melting, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{m}$
\end_inset

, is a more intuitive quantity than the entropy of melting, and is more
 directly measured experimentally.
 At equilibrium for an interface between solid and liquid with a planar
 interface (so the pressure is the same in both phases), the free energies
 of the solid and liquid are equal to one another.
 This fact is generally used to write thermodynamic quantities in terms
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{m}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 We begin by recognizing that the free energy change between solid and liquid
 phases is zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=T_{m}:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{m}(T_{m})=\Delta H_{m}-T_{m}\Delta S_{m}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use this equation to write the entropy of mixing in terms of the
 enthalpy of mixing and the equilibrium melting temperature: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta S_{m}=\frac{\Delta H_{m}}{T_{m}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta T entropy"

\end_inset

 for the melting point depression can therefore be rewritten in the following
 way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{m}-T=\frac{\left(P^{s}-P^{l}\right)V_{m}^{s}T_{m}}{\Delta H_{m}}\label{eq:ps-pl enthalpy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, with 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{s}-P^{\ell}=2\gamma_{s\ell}/r$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{m}-T=\frac{2\gamma_{s\ell}V_{m}^{s}T_{m}}{r\Delta H_{m}}\label{eq:Gibbs-Thomson equation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So how large is this effect? To understand this, we need to put in some
 real numbers.
 Let's consider the case for gold with a particle radius, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of 5 nm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 (solid/liquid interfacial free energy for gold): 0.177 J/m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V_{m}^{s}$
\end_inset

 (molar volume of solid gold): 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\frac{197\,g}{mole}\cdot\frac{cm^{3}}{17.3\,g}\cdot\frac{10^{-6}\,m^{3}}{cm^{3}}=1.14x10^{-5}\,m^{3}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{m}$
\end_inset

 (molar heat of fusion): 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{1.25x10^{4}\,J/mole}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

 (equilibrium melting temperature): 1064 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

C (1337 K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (droplet radius): 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{5x10^{-9}}$
\end_inset

 m
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Putting all these numbers into Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gibbs-Thomson equation"

\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}-T=86$
\end_inset

 K, which is certainly a significant effect.
