\begin_layout Subsubsection
Highly Immiscible Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general the chemical potential of species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is related to its activity coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{i}=\mu_{i}^{0}+RT\ln\left(a_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the gas constant (8.314 J/mole
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

K) 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the absolute temperature and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the chemical potential in it's standard state (which we'll take at a
 pressure of 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

).
 We'll define the standard state chemical potentials as zero, so the chemical
 potentials for 
\begin_inset Formula $P=P^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are simply:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{i}\left(P^{\alpha}\right)=RT\ln\left(a_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\ll1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=H_{i}X$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the Henry's law coefficient.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\approx1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=X_{i}$
\end_inset

 (Raoult's law).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Flat Interface 
\begin_inset Formula $R\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a flat interface the pressures in both phases are equal to the standard
 pressure of 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 The chemical potentials of majority components in each phase (A in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and B in 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

) are given by the following expressions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\mu_{a}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)=RT\ln X_{a}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)\\
\mu_{b}^{\beta}\left(\infty\right)=RT\ln X_{b}^{\beta}\left(\infty\right)
\end{array}\label{eq:Rault's law chempot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can obtain the compositions in the alpha and beta phases at equilibrium
 from chemical potential expressions for the minority phase components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\mu_{a}^{\beta}\left(\infty\right)=RT\ln a_{a}^{\beta}=RT\left[\ln H_{a}+\ln X_{a}^{\beta}\left(\infty\right)\right]\\
\mu_{b}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)=RT\ln a_{b}^{\alpha}=RT\left[\ln H_{b}+\ln X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)\right]
\end{array}\label{eq:Henry's law chempot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a}^{\beta}=1-X_{b}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)=\mu_{a}^{\beta}\left(\infty\right);\,\,\mu_{b}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)=\mu_{b}^{\beta}\left(\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 and solving the whole thing numerically (using MATLAB or some equivalent).
 It's a bit easier in the dilute solution case (relatively large values
 of the Henry's law coefficients, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{b}$
\end_inset

) since we know in this case that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 are going to be very close to one.
 In this situation we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{a}^{\alpha}=\mu_{b}^{\beta}\approx0$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Rault's law chempot"

\end_inset

, so the equations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Henry's law chempot"

\end_inset

 can be solved directly to give 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Curved interface - finite 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chemical potentials are now modified by the pressure contribution to
 the molar free energy of the beta phase, and are no longer zero.
 One consequence of this is that the equilibrium compositions are changed.
 Because the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 phase pressure is taken as our reference pressure, the equations for the
 chemical potentials in this phase are unchanged.
 We just need to specify that 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is no longer infinite:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{a}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)=RT\ln X_{a}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)\label{eq:Rault's law chempot finite r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{b}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)=RT\left[\ln H_{b}+\ln X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the beta phase, we need to account for the fact that pressure in the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phase, 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{\beta}$
\end_inset

, is no longer equal to the reference pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{b}^{\beta}\left(r\right)=RT\ln X_{b}^{\beta}\left(r\right)+\frac{\partial\mu_{b}^{\beta}}{\partial P}\left(P^{\beta}-P^{\alpha}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{a}^{\beta}\left(r\right)=RT\left[\ln H_{a}+\ln X_{a}^{\beta}\left(r\right)\right]+\frac{\partial\mu_{a}^{\beta}}{\partial P}\left(P^{\beta}-P^{\alpha}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pressure derivatives appearing in these equations can be replaced by
 the partial molar volumes of the A and B components in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phase, defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\mu_{i}}{\partial P}=\bar{V}_{i}\label{eq:parital molar volume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can develop some analytic expressions that are useful in the dilute
 limit.
 We'll Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:parital molar volume"

\end_inset

, along with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{\beta}-P^{\alpha}=2\gamma_{\alpha\beta}/r$
\end_inset

 to simplify some of the expressions.
 We're specifically interested in the increase in the minority phase fraction
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 becomes very small.
 In other words, how large is 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

 compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)$
\end_inset

? Requiring that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{b}^{\beta}\left(r\right)=\mu_{b}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
RT\left[\ln H_{b}+\ln X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)\right]=RT\ln X_{b}^{\beta}\left(r\right)+\frac{2\gamma_{\alpha\beta}\bar{V}_{b}}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{b}^{\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Henry's law chempot"

\end_inset

) gives the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln H_{b}=-\ln X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\beta}\approx1$
\end_inset

, so we can ignore the term involving 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(X_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
RT\ln\left(\frac{X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)}{X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(\infty\right)}\right)=\frac{2\gamma_{\alpha\beta}\bar{V}_{b}^{\beta}}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The molar volume of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 precipitate is related to the partial molar volumes in the following way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{m}^{\beta}=X_{a}^{\beta}\bar{V}_{a}^{\beta}+X_{b}^{\beta}\bar{V}_{b}^{\beta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we have 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\beta}\approx1$
\end_inset

 so we can replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{V}_{b}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{m}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{b}^{\alpha}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

