\begin_layout Subsection
Surface energy of a close packed plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use the 'missing bond' picture of crystalline surfaces to estimate
 the surface energy for a close packed plane of atoms.
 Consider, for example a {111} surface in the FCC crystal structure.
 The FCC crystal structure consists of ABC stacking of these close-packed
 planes.
 Consider an atome within one of the 'B' planes within the bulk crystal
 structure.
 Each atom within this close-packed plane has 12 nearest neighbors: 6 in
 same 'B' plane, 3 in the 'A' plane below, 3 in the 'C' plane above.
 Now suppose that this 'B' plane represents the crystal surface.
 We have removed the three bonds to the atoms in the 'C' layer, so that
 we have lost the energy associated with 3 of the 12 nearest neighbor bonds.
 Suppose the energy per bond is 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The bond energy/atom is 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon/2$
\end_inset

 (since the bond energy is shared between the two atoms).
 This means that every surface atom has an excess energy of 
\begin_inset Formula $3\epsilon/2$
\end_inset

 compared to the energy of an atom in the bulk of a material.
 All we need now is an estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The easiest way to get this is to look at the molar 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
heat of sublimation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Heat of sublimation
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{m}$
\end_inset

, which is the energy required to convert one mole of atoms from the solid
 to the vapor.
 If one mole of atoms is vaporized, then 
\begin_inset Formula $zN_{av}/2$
\end_inset

 bonds are broken, where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the number of nearest neighbors for a given atom (12 in our case) and
 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{av}$
\end_inset

 is Avogadro's number.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $z=12$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{m}=12N_{av}\frac{\epsilon}{2}=6N_{av}\epsilon
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearrangement of this equation gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon=L_{m}/6N_{av}\label{eq:bond energy vs enthalpy of sublimation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so the surface energy per atom is 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{m}/4N_{av}$
\end_inset

.
 There is also an excess entropy associated with the surface due to changes
 in the vibrations of the surface atoms, configuration entropy due to surface
 vacancies, but this is typically a small contribution to the overall surface
 free energy and is ignored in our treatment.
 The surface energy is obtained by multiplying the excess surface energy
 per atom by the surface density of atoms on the plane of interest, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{s}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{sv}=\frac{3\epsilon\Sigma_{s}}{2}\label{eq:gamma vs bond density}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combination of Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
