\begin_layout Subsection
Orientation Dependence of the Surface Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to understand the faceting of single crystals we need to understand
 the anisotropy of the surface energy.
 The existence of this anisotropy is one of the key differences between
 a liquid and a solid.
 We can use simple bond counting arguments to understand where this anisotropy
 comes from, using drawing shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bonds on a tilted surface"

\end_inset

.
 This figure shows a square lattice of atoms with an exposed surface tilted
 by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 with respect to one of the crystal axes.
 The only way to get this tilted surface is to add a series of atomic steps,
 each of which leaves a broken bond at the top and left surfaces.
 Consider surface of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 along the surface of the material.
 The projection of this length onto the horizontal axis is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 and the projection onto the vertical axis is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Along each of these directions the distance between broken bonds is 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, so the total number of bonds is along the length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ell/a\right)\left(\cos\theta+\sin\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The number of bonds along the width of the sample (the direction perpendicular
 to the plane of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bonds on a tilted surface"

\end_inset

) is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $w/a$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is the sample width.
 The number of bonds per unit area, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{s}$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sigma_{s}=\frac{1}{a^{2}}\left(\cos\theta+\sin\theta\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The surface energy is obtained multiplying by the energy per bond, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon/2:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{sv}\approx\frac{\epsilon}{2a^{2}}\left(\cos\theta+\sin\theta\right)\label{eq:gamma vs theta no ab value}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The equation is approximate because we have not accounted for any entropic
 contributions to the surface free energy.
 Also, the model of just adding up the contributions from 'missing' bonds
 neglects the tendency for the atoms at the surface to reorganize into structure
s that lower the overall free energy.
 These surface reconstructions play an important role in the surface science
 of materials
\end_layout

