\begin_layout Standard
In the two dimensional Wulff construction the interface surface of interest
 is specified by a single variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For a true, three-dimensional crystal the Wulff circle becomes a Wulff
 sphere, and we need two different angles to specify the the orientation
 on this sphere.
 In other words, we have two degrees of freedom in specifying a specific
 surface of a three-dimensional crystal.
 We commonly specify a surface by using the normal vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

, that is perpendicular to that surface.
 This surface has three components, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}$
\end_inset

, in the x, y and z directions, respectively:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{n}=\left(n_{1}\hat{x}+n_{2}\hat{y}+n_{3}\hat{z}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}^{2}+n_{2}^{2}+n_{3}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, only two of the three components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

 are independent, so we again come to the conclusion that there are two
 degrees of freedom associated with the specification of a crystal surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to fully describe a grain boundary between two crystals we need
 to specify three additional degrees of freedom, so there are five degrees
 of freedom altogether.
 In order to illustrate these degrees of freedom, we can consider the following
 conceptual procedure for producing a grain boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Cut the crystal along a plane specified by the unit normal to the plane,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Two degrees of freedom are associated with the specification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rotate one of the two halves of the crystal by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 about an axis directed along the unit normal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two additional degrees of freedom are used in the specification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

, just as we use two degrees of freedom to specify 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The fifth and final degree of freedom is the the rotation angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that 5 different parameters are needed to specify a grain boundary
 within a given crystal means that it is impossible for us to be exhaustive
 in our treatment of the different possibilities.
 Instead, we'll consider the following three cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Twist boundary
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Twist boundary
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Twist boundaries correspond to rotation about an axis that is perpendicular
 to the plane.
 In terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

, they correspond to the case where these unit vectors are parallel to one
 another:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{c}\parallel\hat{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tilt boundary
\end_layout

\end_inset

