\begin_layout Subsection
Elastic Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Precipitates may transition from coherent to incoherent as they grow because
 of the elastic energy associated with the lattice distortions imposed by
 a lattice parameter mismatch across the interface.
 Consider a spherical precipitate of phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 in a matrix of phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, as illustrated schematically Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Beta-precipitate-in alpha"

\end_inset

.
 We'll suppose for our case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 have the same crystal structure, and that for small values of precipitate
 radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 the interfacial free energy is isotropic.
 Because the interface is coherent it includes only a chemical component
 of the interfacial free energy, which we refer to here as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ch}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{\alpha\beta}=\gamma_{ch}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/beta spherical precipitate.svg
	width 20text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Beta precipitate in a matrix of alpha.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Beta-precipitate-in alpha"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the lattice parameters of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phases do not match exactly, which will almost certainly be the case for
 any real system, there will be a positive elastic strain energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{el}$
\end_inset

 that we need to consider.
 For a spherical, coherent precipitate in an elastically isotropic medium,
 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{el}$
\end_inset

 is given by the following expression: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{el}=V^{\beta}\left[\frac{18\delta^{2}G^{\alpha}K^{\beta}}{3K^{\beta}+4G^{\alpha}}\right]\label{eq:elastic energy for spherical inclusion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\beta}$
\end_inset

= bulk modulus of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phase: 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\beta}=V\frac{\partial P}{\partial V^{\beta}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

= shear modulus of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 phase: 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathrm{\frac{shear\,stress}{shear\,strain}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

= misfit: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{1}{3}\left[\frac{V_{m}^{\beta}-V_{m}^{\alpha}}{V_{m}^{\alpha}}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For cubic systems and for the small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 that are generally relevant here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is also equal to the fractional mismatch in the lattice parameter:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta=\left(\frac{a^{\beta}-a^{\alpha}}{a^{\alpha}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To provide some more insight into the behavior of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:elastic energy for spherical inclusion"

\end_inset

 we consider the following three limiting cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
compressible precipitate in a rigid matrix: 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\alpha}>>K^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{W_{el}}{V^{\beta}}\approx\frac{9\delta^{2}K^{\beta}}{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
rigid precipitate in a deformable matrix: 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\beta}>>G^{\alpha}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{W_{el}}{V^{\beta}}\approx6\delta^{2}G^{\alpha}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Precipitate and matrix with the same elastic properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
An isotropic material is characterized by just two independent elastic constants.
 It's convenient to express 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, using the following expression (note that the Wikipedia page has a very
 useful summary of the relationships between different elastic constants
 for an isotropic material)
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "_poissons_2014"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K=\frac{2G\nu}{1-2\nu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example, we can take 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=1/3,$
\end_inset

 in which case we get 
\begin_inset Formula $K=2G,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{el}$
\end_inset

 is given by the following expression.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{W_{el}}{V^{\beta}}=3.6\delta^{2}G
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
In each of these cases the most important points to keep in mind are the
 following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The elastic strain energy is proportional to the volume of the precipitate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The elastic strain energy is proportional to the square of the lattice mismatch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now in a position to compare the overall free energy of coherent
 and incoherent precipitates, and to see how each of these depend on the
 precipitate size.
 For a coherent precipitate we just need to add the elastic strain energy
 to the chemical contribution to the interfacial free energy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{coh}=4\pi r^{2}\left(\gamma_{ch}\right)+\frac{4}{3}\pi r^{3}\frac{W_{el}}{V^{\beta}}\label{eq:coherent ppt energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incoherent precipitates have a larger value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 because we also need to account for the structural component of the interfacial
 free energy that arises for the dislocations that are present at the interface
 between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 phases.
 However, the strain energy in the bulk is reduced to zero, so have the
 following for 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{inc}$
\end_inset

, the total excess free energy of an incoherent precipitate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{inc}=4\pi r^{2}\left(\gamma_{ch}+\gamma_{st}\right)\label{eq:incoherent ppt energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For suitably small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r,$
\end_inset

 the contribution to the total free energy that scales with 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}$
\end_inset

 will always be more important than the contribution that scales with 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 As a result 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{coh}$
\end_inset

 will always be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{inc}$
\end_inset

 for sufficiently small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 As the precipitate grows and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 increases, the contribution that scales with 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{3}$
\end_inset

 will become more important, and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{coh}$
\end_inset

 will exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{inc}$
\end_inset

.
 The two free energies are equal to one another at a critical radius, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{crit,}$
\end_inset

 which we illustrate schematically in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:coherent and incoherent ppt energies"

\end_inset

.
 Precipitates will remain coherent for sizes below 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{crit}$
\end_inset

 and will become incoherent for sizes larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{crit}$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{crit}$
\end_inset

 is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{coh}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{inc}$
\end_inset

 are equal to one another.
 From Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coherent ppt energy"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:incoherent ppt energy"

\end_inset

 we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{crit}=3\gamma_{st}\frac{V^{\beta}}{W_{el}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

