\begin_layout Subsection
Effects of Elastic Anisotropy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in reality, no crystalline material is completely isotropic.
 An FCC crystal, for example, is generally stiffest along the [110] directions
 and softest along [100] directions.
 This is because the linear density of atoms is highest along the [110]
 direction, where in a hard sphere model of the crystal structure the atoms
 are in contact with one another.
 As a result coherent precipitaes end up with facets perpendicular to the
 'soft' [100] directions.
 Faceting becomes more important as the precipitates grow (assuming they
 stay coherent), since the elastic contribution to the energy scales with
 the volume of the precipitate, whereas the total surface area scales with
 the 2/3 power of the volume.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Three Phase Contact Lines
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Three phase contact lines
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two regions of space meet at a plane, and three regions of space meet at
 a line.
 These lines are important in a variety of problems in materials science.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:threephasecontact"

\end_inset

 we consider the most general case, where the 3 regions of space are labeled
 1, 2 and 3.
 The junction between these three regions may correspond to three different
 material phases, or they may correspond to grain boundaries within a single
 phase region.
 In either case we refer to 1, 2 and 3 as 'phases', and refer to the line
 at which they meet as a '3-phase contact line'.
 The way in which the three phases meet at this contact line are specified
 by two angles.
 These two angles can be defined in a variety of ways, but we use the angles
 defined in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:threephasecontact"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

, which give the orientation of the 1/3 and 2/3 boundaries with respect
 to the 1/2 boundary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 are related to the interfacial free energies of the 3 phases that meet
 at the contact line.
 Because interfaces have a contribution to the free energy that is associated
 with them, there is a thermodynamic driving force for any interface to
 shrink in area.
 As a result an interface exerts a force on the contact line along the direction
 of the interface, with a force per length of equal to the relevant interfacial
 free energy.
 At the three phase contact line three different forces, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{12}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{23}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{13}$
\end_inset

, are pulling on the contact line.
 At equilibrium the net force on the contact line is zero.
 We can obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 by considering separate force balances in the directions parallel and perpendic
ular to the 1/2 interface:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Perpendicular force balance:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{13}\sin\theta_{1}=\gamma_{23}\sin\theta_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Horizontal force balance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{12}=\gamma_{13}\cos\theta_{1}+\gamma_{23}\cos\theta_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are coupled, nonlinear equations that generally need to be solved
 numerically.
 An example procedure using MATLAB is given below in the section on wetting.
\end_layout

