\begin_layout Standard
We can now consider wetting in solid systems, where elastic strain energy
 often plays a role.
 Here we consider the example of a thin, germanium film that is deposited
 on a silicon substrate.
 Both of these elements have the diamond cubic crystal structure, with a
 lattice parameter mismatch of about 4%.
 When an element like germanium is deposited from the vapor phase, the atoms
 land individually on the substrate as illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Ge deposition process"

\end_inset

.
 If the atoms have sufficient mobility, the resulting film will be determined
 by the structure that minimizes the free energy.
 For the Ge/Si system, the equilibrium structure consists of a thin, continuous
 wetting layer below isolated Ge islands.
 
\end_layout

