name "fig:Ge deposition process"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the full behavior of the system, it is useful to develop a
 plot of the overall free energy per unit area of the system as a function
 of the Ge film thickness, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{Ge}$
\end_inset

, which we show in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Ge free energy vs. thickness"

\end_inset

.
 The following contributions to the free energy need to be considered:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{Si}$
\end_inset

: The surface free energy of the Si substrate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{Ge}$
\end_inset

: The surface free energy of Ge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{Ch}$
\end_inset

: The chemical contribution to the free energy of the Si/Ge interface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{St}$
\end_inset

: The structural component to the free energy of the Si/Ge interface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $W_{el}/A$
\end_inset

: The strain energy per unit area within the Ge film.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full thickness dependence of the free energy can be understood by investigat
ing the way that these contributions contribute to the overall free energy
 as the Ge film thickness increases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{Ge}=0$
\end_inset

 the free energy is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{Si}$
\end_inset

, the surface free energy of the silicon substrate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For very thin Ge films the elastic strain energy within the Ge film does
 not contribute significantly to the strain energy, so the overall value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $W/A$
\end_inset

 is the sum of the energies of the Si/Ge and Ge/vapor interfaces.
 Because the Si/Ge interface is fully coherent for sufficiently thin Ge
 films, its interfacial free energy is just the chemical part, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ch}$
\end_inset

, so the overall free energy for very thin Ge films is 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{Ge}$
\end_inset

 + 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{Ch}$
\end_inset

.
 This free energy is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{Si}$
\end_inset

, so the system is in the wetting regime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As the film thickness increases the Ge film remains coherent, but 
\begin_inset Formula $W/A$
\end_inset

 increases linearly with thickness, according to the thickness dependence
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{el}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When the elastic energy exceeds the structural component of the Si/Ge interfacia
l free energy associated with the loss of full coherence, the Ge film becomes
 incoherent.
 The elastic energy 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{el}$
\end_inset

